@* This exemplar Search ingestion tool proves the Search module can contribute additional singleton tools without bypassing the shared Workbench contracts. *@
<section class="search-ingestion-tool" aria-labelledby="search-ingestion-tool-title">
    <header class="search-ingestion-tool__header">
        <p class="search-ingestion-tool__eyebrow">Search module</p>
        <h1 id="search-ingestion-tool-title">Search ingestion</h1>
        <p>
            This dummy ingestion surface reserves space for future ingestion workflows while proving the module can contribute
            multiple tools, explorer items, and singleton activation targets through the shared Workbench shell.
        </p>
    </header>

    <div class="search-ingestion-tool__content">
        <section>
            <h2>Planned ingestion focus</h2>
            <ul>
                <li>Monitor ingestion requests and recent pipeline activity.</li>
                <li>Summarize provider inputs and indexing outcomes.</li>
                <li>Expose future command-driven ingestion operations without changing the shell model.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section>
            <h2>Current fixed Workbench context</h2>
            <dl class="search-ingestion-tool__context-list">
                @foreach (var contextEntry in ContextValues)
                {
                    <div>
                        <dt>@contextEntry.Key</dt>
                        <dd>@(string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(contextEntry.Value) ? "(empty)" : contextEntry.Value)</dd>
                    </div>
                }
            </dl>
        </section>
    </div>
</section>
